Halve, peel, and thinly slice the @yellow onion{1}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Remove and discard the ribs and stems from the @collard greens{1%bunch}, then slice the leaves into thin ribbons. Mince the @chili pepper{1}, removing the seeds if you prefer less heat.

Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium heat. Add the onion and cook, tossing, for about ~{5%minutes}, until softened. Add the garlic and as much chili pepper as you dare (we used ¼ teaspoon!) to the pan and cook for another ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

Increase the heat to medium-high. Add the @ground beef{10%ounce}, @turmeric{1%teaspoon}, and @curry powder{1%teaspoon} to the pan and cook, breaking up the pieces, until browned but not yet cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Bring 2 cups of water and 1 @veggie stock concentrate{1} to a boil in a #small pot{}.

Add the collard greens, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, and ½ cup water to the pan with the beef and cook, another ~{4-5%minutes}, until collards are very soft and sauce has thickened. Season with salt and pepper.

While the collard greens cook, make the polenta: when water is boiling, stir in the @grits{1%cup} and cook ~{2-3%minutes}, stirring often, until thick. Remove from the heat, stir in the @sour cream{2%tablespoon} and @butter{}, then season with salt and pepper.

> If your polenta is too thick, add a splash of water. If it's too thin, let it simmer away until thickened.

Serve the Jamaican beef on a bed of polenta and dig in!